Following the hints, we have

\begin{align*}
\ln y &= \ln\left((\sin x)^{\sin x}\right) = \sin x \ln(\sin x)\end{align*}

Differentiating both sides yields

\begin{align*}
\frac{y'}{y}&= (\cos x)\ln(\sin x) + (\sin x)\tfrac{d}{dx}\ln(\sin x) \quad \text{(product rule)}\\
\frac{y'}{y}&= (\cos x)\ln(\sin x) + (\sin x)(\cos x)\cdot\frac{1}{\sin x} \quad \text{(chain rule)}\\
\frac{y'}{y}&= (\cos x)\ln(\sin x) + \cos x \\
y'&= y\cos(x)(\ln(\sin x) + 1 )\end{align*}

Finally, plugging in \emph{y} yields the final answer

\begin{align*}\displaystyle
y' = (\sin x)^{\sin x}\cos(x)(\ln(\sin x) + 1 )\end{align*}
